        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Hoffmann refers to the German translation of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref>, Carus trans. 1868. In the English edition, the passage referred to is <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref> 1: 259: ‘Golden-spangled Polish fowls are said to have the skin between their toes much developed; Mr. Tegetmeier observed this in one bird, but it was not so in one which I examined.’</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD referred to Hoffmann’s sketch in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7952.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, 1: 272. <hi rend="italic">Anas boschas</hi> (now <hi rend="italic">A. platyrhynchos</hi>, the mallard) is the wild ancestor of most domestic ducks.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><hi rend="italic">Phasianus gallus</hi> var. <hi rend="italic">domesticus</hi> is now <hi rend="italic">Gallus gallus domesticus</hi>, the domestic fowl. <hi rend="italic">Mas</hi>: male.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4"><hi rend="italic">Von oben</hi>: from above (German).</note>
